/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:9:**Sources consulted:** Vasseur 2007 preprint; Vasseur lecture notes (DGPekin.pdf); CKN Seminar Notes Ulm 2019 (Skipper); Seregin-Shilkin survey arXiv:1402.7181; Lee REU paper 2024 (De Giorgi for fluids).
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:29:2. **Fixed scale, not shrinking.** The domain [−1,1]×B(1) does not shrink as the proof proceeds. The De Giorgi cylinders Q_k converge to [−1/2,1]×B(1/2) from the outside. This is the fundamental structural departure from CKN, where the epsilon-regularity criterion is stated as a condition at every radius r → 0.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:31:3. **Direct L∞ bound.** The conclusion is u ∈ L∞, not just u ∈ L^p for some high p. The De Giorgi iteration is specifically designed to produce L∞ bounds via level-set energy estimates.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:83:The covering argument is entirely at the level of Theorem 2 — the De Giorgi iteration (Theorem 1) is used only to establish Theorem 2, after which the CKN covering machinery runs unchanged.
